 Description

This workflow will restore a database from an existing database backup file.  The default deployment will only show required parameters.  Run the Discovery workflow afterwards to verify that database has been restored.

 Required Inputs

    Server Target - The desired target to run this flow against.
    Server Target Username - The user to login to the Server Target as.
    Server Target Password - The password to login as the Server Target Username.
    Download Source Host - The target host where the files needed for this flow can be downloaded from.
    Download Source Path - The path to where the files can be found on the Download Source Host.
    Database Backup File - *Required. The path to the database backup file in the Software Repository. If file already exists on local system, ensure that the filename is entered into this field, and the file's directory is entered into the "Download Target Destination" parameter.
    Download Target Destination - *Required. The directory where the database backup file should be stored. If it doesn't exist in this directory, it will be downloaded from the software repository, using the path provided in the "Download From Software Directory" parameter.
    Instance.Name - No description

 Optional Inputs

    Clean Code Base - Remove code base from target after execution (True || False).
    Clean JRE - Remove JRE from target after execution (True || False).
    Download From SA - Download binaries from SA (True || False). Must set override for 'SAUser' System Account.
    SA Folder Path - Location of binaries on SA. Must set override for 'SAUser' System Account.
    Debug Level - Set level of output [(least) 1-5 (most)]
    Overwrite Existing Database - Optional. If set to "YES", workflow will only overwrite if the databse already exists.  Use this. Acceptable values\: Yes, No
    Run Simulation Only - Optional. If set to "YES", workflow will only run Pre-Restore Validation.  Use this mode to discover the original data and log files used for the database backup.  Acceptable values\: Yes, No
    Reindex Restored Database - Optional. If set to "YES", workflow will reindex the database after Restore is successfully completed. Acceptable values\: Yes, No
    Database Name - Optional. To restore backup file with a new database name.  If left blank, original database name will be used.
    Log File Locations - Optional. A comma-delimited list of directories or full file paths for each log file in the backup file.  Use "Run Simulation Only" mode to discover the number of log files in backup file.  If not filename is provided in the location, the original log filename will be used.
    Backup Encryption Password - Optional.  If the backup file is encrypted with a password, provide password.  To prevent the password from showing in the Deployment screen, use a password-based Policy.
    Data File Locations - Optional. A comma-delimited list of directories or full file paths for each data file in the backup file.  Use Run Simulation Only to discover the number of data files in backup file.  If not filename is provided in the location, the original data filename will be used.
    Instance Password - Optional - The password of the Windows account that will be performing the patch operation.
    Preserve Users and Roles - Optional. If set to "YES", workflow will try to preserve the roles and users if the database already exists and recreate in the restored database. Acceptable values\: Yes, No

 Dependencies

A SQL Server 2008/2008 R2/2012/2014 instance should already be provisioned.
Database backup file should be available locally, on Windows network share, or on SA software repository
   If the workflow fails to restore from the path, then the SQL Service is running as an account that cannot access the path (like LocalSystem).  Change the running service to an admin-level account, and try again.  The Provisioning workflows have an advanced parameter called SQL Service Account/Password that the user can set to a user with admin rights.

 Results Verification

- Run the Discovery workflow afterwards to verify that database has been restored.
- In the last step, the workflow verifies that the new database exists.
- Connect to the target instance via a command-line tool (like sqlcmd) or GUI-based program (like SQL Server Management Studio).  Run "select * from master.dbo.sysdatabases where name \= ''" to verify that new database exists.



 Additional Documentation

Additional information, including the _HP Database and Middleware Automation Support Matrix_ and solution pack user guides, are available via HP Live Network\:

"http\://hpln.hp.com/group/database-and-middleware-automation"\:http\://hpln.hp.com/group/database-and-middleware-automation

To access the documentation, click the RESOURCES link and enter your HP Passport credentials.
